<methodology slug="feature-discovery">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>user-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Six-step process for identifying and prioritizing features: collect sources, categorize with Kano, score opportunity, estimate effort, prioritize with RICE, validate before build.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>feature-discovery</tag>
      <tag>product-prioritization</tag>
      <tag>user-research</tag>
      <tag>rice-framework</tag>
      <tag>kano-model</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Feature Discovery</title>

    <summary>Six-step process for identifying, validating, and prioritizing product features: collect from four sources, categorize with Kano model, score opportunity, estimate effort, prioritize with RICE, then validate top candidates before engineering commitment.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Feature decisions based on gut feeling or the loudest customer request produce features nobody uses and miss features that drive adoption. The six-step process separates discovery from prioritization — a critical distinction because collected feature requests describe symptoms, not jobs. RICE scoring forces explicit effort estimation before commitment; Kano categorization prevents building Delighters before Must-haves are solid.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quarterly roadmap planning when the backlog is full but priorities are unclear.</item>
        <item>Post-launch: identifying what to build next based on usage data and support tickets.</item>
        <item>Competitive gap analysis: discovering features rivals have but your product lacks.</item>
        <item>Before running a user survey: generate a candidate feature list to score.</item>
        <item>Synthesizing a large feature request log (50+ items) into actionable clusters.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>When the core product is not yet working — feature discovery before PMF is premature optimization.</item>
        <item>Replacing direct customer conversations: analytics and ticket logs supplement but do not replace qualitative insight.</item>
        <item>When only one vocal customer is requesting a feature — frequency matters; one loud voice is not signal.</item>
        <item>When the team has already committed to a roadmap for the current quarter — discovery is for next cycle.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="step-1-collect-from-four-sources">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Collect feature ideas from all four source types before scoring: Customer Research (interviews, support tickets, churn conversations, NPS detractors), Usage Analytics (adoption rates, drop-off points, error rates), Competitive Analysis (competitor features and gaps, negative reviews), Market Trends (industry reports, technology and regulatory changes).</statement>
        <rationale>Single-source discovery creates blind spots; analytics reveal what users do but not why; interviews reveal why but not how often; competitive analysis reveals expectations but not differentiation opportunities.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Cap the candidate list at 20 items per discovery cycle — scoring 50+ features creates decision paralysis.</statement>
        <rationale>A list longer than 20 means the collection phase wasn't selective enough; the scoring step becomes a distraction rather than a decision tool.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-2-kano-categorization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Categorize each feature into one of four Kano types: Must-have (basic expectations; absence causes dissatisfaction), Performance (more = more satisfaction), Delight/Excitement (unexpected; creates delight if present), Indifferent (customers don't care). Build Must-haves before Delighters.</statement>
        <rationale>Delighters built on a shaky Must-have foundation fail to retain customers; users who can't log in are not impressed by AI suggestions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-3-opportunity-scoring">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Score each feature: Opportunity = Importance + max(Importance - Satisfaction, 0). Scale Importance and Satisfaction 1-10. High opportunity = high importance AND low satisfaction. Flag any score above 10 as high priority.</statement>
        <rationale>Features users find highly important but poorly served by current solutions are the highest-value targets; the formula penalizes well-served needs and rewards underserved ones.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-4-effort-estimation">
      <p>Effort categories: XS (less than 1 day), S (1-3 days), M (1-2 weeks), L (2-4 weeks), XL (1-3 months). Engineering lead must validate all effort estimates before RICE scores drive roadmap decisions — agent estimates are not acceptable inputs.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="step-5-rice-prioritization">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Compute RICE = (Reach x Impact x Confidence) / Effort. Reach = users per quarter; Impact = 0.25/0.5/1/2/3; Confidence = 50%/80%/100%; Effort = person-weeks. Sort descending; validate top 3 before committing to build.</statement>
        <rationale>RICE prevents high-effort low-reach features from crowding out low-effort high-reach features; the confidence multiplier forces honest assessment of evidence quality.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="step-6-validate-before-building">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Validate top-RICE features before committing: Fake door test (low effort, medium confidence), Prototype (medium effort, high confidence), Wizard of Oz (medium effort, high confidence), Limited beta (high effort, very high confidence), Pre-sales (medium effort, very high confidence).</statement>
        <rationale>RICE scoring is based on estimates; pre-build validation with real users replaces estimates with behavioral evidence before engineering investment begins.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="worked-example-saas-dashboard-clutter">
      <example type="good" title="SaaS Dashboard Clutter">
        <note>Problem: dashboard too cluttered, key metrics buried. Discovery: 15 interviews ("what do you look for first?"), analytics (80% of users view only 3 of 12 widgets), 23 support tickets requesting simpler view. Features identified with RICE: Customizable dashboard (1200), Focus mode (900), Saved views (600). Validation: prototype test with 10 users, 8/10 preferred simplified view. Decision: build Focus mode first — highest RICE, lowest effort.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="worked-example-mobile-app-low-dau">
      <example type="good" title="Mobile App Low DAU">
        <note>Problem: low daily active users after download. Discovery: churn interviews ("I forget the app exists"), analytics (90% never enable notifications), competitor analysis (push notifications with value). Features by Opportunity Score: Smart notifications (16), Daily digest (12), Widget for home screen (10). Decision: A/B test notification types first, then build widget.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Building every feature request without prioritization.</description>
        <reason>Feature bloat reduces the product's core value proposition; every added feature increases maintenance cost and user confusion.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No validation step between RICE scoring and engineering commitment.</description>
        <reason>RICE scores are estimates; without behavioral validation, the team builds on assumptions, not evidence.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Copying a competitor feature without understanding why they built it.</description>
        <reason>A competitor feature may exist for a different customer segment or job; copying it without context wastes effort and may confuse your users.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Weighting feature requests equally regardless of customer segment value.</description>
        <reason>A feature requested by 50 free-tier users may be less valuable than one requested by 5 enterprise customers; segment value must factor into prioritization.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Generating RICE confidence scores without explicit evidence assessment.</description>
        <reason>Agent-generated confidence scores are opinions, not evidence assessments; confidence must reflect the quality and quantity of actual validation data collected.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="key-distinctions">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Separate "what customers ask for" from "what job they need done" before writing any feature spec. Request: "export to Excel" — Job: "share data with my finance team."</statement>
        <rationale>Building the stated request often misses better solutions to the underlying job; understanding the job opens a wider solution space.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-integration-limitations">
      <p>Agents cannot query your analytics platform directly without tool integration (Amplitude, Mixpanel, etc.). RICE scoring and Kano categorization are heuristic; numbers suggest precision that does not exist. Feature requests often describe symptoms, not jobs; an agent will synthesize what customers said, not what they need. Opportunity score math (importance + importance - satisfaction) produces misleading results for poorly-worded surveys. Agents have no way to assess implementation effort without engineering input — effort estimates must come from humans.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A well-structured feature discovery pipeline uses three agent passes: (1) collection — agent processes raw input (support tickets, interview notes, review exports) and produces a candidate feature list; (2) categorization — agent classifies each feature by Kano type and drafts opportunity scores from stated importance/satisfaction pairs; (3) prioritization — agent computes RICE scores using human-provided effort and reach estimates. The human's role is to supply data, validate categorization, and make the final prioritization call.</p>
      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent for running discovery tasks within an SDD feature plan. Any general Claude subagent for processing support ticket exports, generating candidate feature lists, and computing RICE scores.</p>
      <p>Agent-generated Kano categorization is opinion-based without actual customer survey data; treat it as a starting hypothesis. LLMs will over-represent features requested in their training data (e.g., dark mode, mobile app) — cross-check against your actual ticket log. RICE confidence scores must come from humans; an agent cannot assess how solid the evidence base is. Human checkpoint: engineering lead must validate all effort estimates before RICE scores drive roadmap decisions. Agents conflate feature requests into overly broad categories; instruct to preserve specific, distinct items ("bulk actions" vs. "batch email send").</p>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/discovery-board.md" purpose="Feature discovery board with collection, categorization, scoring, and validation plan."/>
      <template path="templates/feature-request-log.md" purpose="Per-feature request log with metadata, impact, validation, and decision fields."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-extract-features.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to extract feature candidates from support tickets."/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-opportunity-score.txt" purpose="LLM prompt to compute Opportunity Scores from survey data."/>
      <template path="templates/rice-scorer.py" purpose="RICE score calculator for a feature candidate list."/>
    </templates>

